# =============================================================================
# AIMS OS — initramfs module list
# =============================================================================
# Each line names a kernel module that initramfs-tools must include in the
# initrd image. Modules listed here load BEFORE the root filesystem is
# mounted — this is the only way to ensure they're available during the
# very early boot phase.
#
# Why we force these:
#   virtio_gpu / virtio_pci
#       arm64 QEMU/UTM virtual machines use virtio-gpu-pci for graphics.
#       The Debian arm64 kernel builds virtio_gpu as a *module* (not
#       built-in), and the default initramfs doesn't pull it in. Result:
#       the framebuffer doesn't appear until much later in boot, and the
#       Plymouth splash window (which runs from the initramfs) silently
#       skips because there's nowhere to draw. RedHat bug 1593028 has
#       the canonical context; Fedora fixed it by patching dracut to
#       include virtio_gpu in their initramfs, and we do the equivalent
#       here for initramfs-tools on Bookworm.
#
#       virtio_pci is virtio_gpu's transport dependency — listing it is
#       belt-and-braces (Debian's modules.dep should pull it in
#       automatically, but the line makes the intent explicit and
#       protects us if module graphs change in a future kernel).
#
# This is the canonical fix; it has zero regression on real hardware
# (Raspberry Pi 4/5, x86 laptops) where the framebuffer appears early
# regardless of whether virtio_gpu is in the initramfs.
# =============================================================================
virtio_gpu
virtio_pci
